Date: Sat 14 Nov 2015
Source: Times of Oman [edited]
http://www.timesofoman.com/article/71721/Oman/Health/The-contagious-'hand-foot-and-mouth-disease'-HFMD-among-children-is-spreading-in-Oman


A surge in the contagious 'hand, foot and mouth disease' (HFMD) among children is keeping doctors busy at the private hospitals in Oman. Dr A Parthasarathi, specialist paediatrician and neonatologist at the Badr Al Samaa Hospital, said the virus is spreading in Oman. "We are currently seeing around 10 to 12 cases in our outpatient department every day," he revealed.

Dr Santosh Ramaswamy, paediatrician at the Atlas Medical Hospital, said the disease is characterised by a mild fever, painful sores in the mouth and rashes with blisters on hands and feet. "It comes in specific areas where sores may be painful," he stated. Ramaswamy also said the virus is easily spread through coughing and sneezing, and often the disease breaks out within a community. "Initially, your child may feel tired, get a sore throat, or have a mild fever. Then, sores or blisters may appear in the mouth, feet, and sometimes the buttocks," doctors said.

Since most HFMD symptoms resemble those of chickenpox, another contagious viral infection, many parents can be easily misled, warned experts. "Although this disease runs its course without requiring any treatment, it is important for parents to still visit a paediatrician," doctors said.

In case of chickenpox, children develop rashes, mainly on the body near the abdomen areas and head. "The blisters look different from those in the case of HFMD," Ramaswamy said. Though hand-foot-and-mouth disease is common among children, it can also occur in adults during periods when the weather is changing.

Cases of chicken pox and scarlet fever have also been reported in various parts of the country. "The infections and fever are common, as winter is setting in. The number of people taking to bed will keep increasing whenever there is a gap between maximum and minimum temperatures," doctors said. "The best thing to do this season is to practice good hygiene and wash hands regularly, as a good hand wash will kill the virus," they added.

The Indian School Jaalan Bani Bu Ali had to recently declare a 10-day holiday for 1 class after more than 15 students in 1 particular grade had contracted chicken pox.

