[The following has been mostly extracted from the comments of moderator Craig Pringle in prior ProMED-mail posts on this subject:

Hand, foot, and mouth disease (HFMD) is caused by a group of RNA viruses called enteroviruses that includes polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, echoviruses, and enteroviruses. Coxsackievirus A16 is the most common cause of HFMD in the United States, but other coxsackieviruses can also cause the illness. Only rarely is the precise agent identified because the outcome of infection is generally benign. However, enterovirus 71 has been associated with more severe disease, such as encephalitis.

HFMD is characterized by fever, malaise, painful sores in the mouth and a rash on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet, as well as a rash around the mouth, over the knees, and on the buttocks or genital area. Pictures of the oral and skin lesions can be found at http://www.ijdvl.com/article.asp?issn=0378-6323;year=2013;volume=79;issue=2;spage=165;epage=175;aulast=Sarma. Temporary fingernail and toenail loss, called onychomadesis, have been reported, occurring mostly in children within a few weeks after having HFMD.

HFMD is commonly spread via the fecal-oral route, blister fluid, and respiratory secretions. Generally, a person with HFMD is most contagious during the 1st week of illness. People can sometimes be contagious for days or weeks after symptoms go away. Some people, especially adults, may not develop any symptoms, but they can still spread the virus to others. This is why susceptible individuals should always try to maintain good hygiene to reduce exposure to any of the enteroviruses associated with HFMD. HFMD is not transmitted to or from pets or other animals. There is no specific vector.

Regarding grading of HFMD, from the Academia website:
"Grade 1 is uncomplicated fever along with rash on the hands, feet and mouth; grade 2 shows twitching in the ﬁngers indicating nervous system afﬂiction. In Grade 3 disease manifests with more serious symptoms: persistent fever, lethargy, irritability, limb weakness, meningism, and seizure. Grade 4 is the most serious level of disease, presenting with cardiorespiratory compromise. Grading is useful for deciding treatment options: child presenting with grade 2 should be hospitalized and carefully observed for further progression. At grade 3 and 4, the child's life is seriously at risk, and intensive care becomes a necessity." (http://www.academia.edu/9587522/Big_Picture_Clinical_metamorphosis_of_hand_foot_and_mouth_disease_HFMD.) - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3794098,124.]
